{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:41:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:41:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13799"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13799"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.39,0.1,0.07,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6416"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112517"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6416"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13799"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94551"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"626"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12637"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46196"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112517"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of abdominal pain, distension, and constipation. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly unwell. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended, with tenderness and guarding in the right lower quadrant (Image 1). Bowel sounds are high-pitched. An abdominal X-ray is performed (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rigid sigmoidoscopy","Laparotomy","Percutaneous caecostomy","Colonoscopy","Conservative management with nasogastric decompression"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and X-ray findings in this case are consistent with a caecal volvulus. The abdominal X-ray characteristically shows the dilated caecum in an atypical position and this is often in the left upper quadrant. In this case there is an obvious asymmetrical distension of the abdomen. The finding of a localised area of tenderness is of concern, as when this is combined with the radiological finding highly suggestive of a caecal volvulus, points very strongly to an ischaemic process. In any case of volvulus, ischaemia is a real risk when the mesenteric supply is put in jeopardy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive management for caecal volvulus. It allows for direct visualisation of the bowel, detorsion of the volvulus, assessment of bowel viability and, if necessary. This approach must be undertaken promptly and is crucial to prevent ischaemia and perforation, which are serious complications of untreated caecal volvulus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERigid sigmoidoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for caecal volvulus. This procedure is sometimes used for diagnosing and potentially treating sigmoid volvulus, but it cannot reach the caecum and is therefore ineffective for caecal volvulus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended in caecal volvulus due to the high risk of perforation. Unlike sigmoid volvulus, endoscopic decompression is generally not successful or safe in caecal volvulus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management with nasogastric decompression\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for caecal volvulus. While it may provide temporary relief, it does not address the underlying mechanical obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous caecostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used as a temporising measure in high-risk patients who cannot tolerate surgery. It can provide decompression and reduce the risks of ischaemia and perforation. However, it is not the definitive management for caecal volvulus in a patient who can tolerate surgery, as it does not address the underlying volvulus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Caecal volvulus typically presents with abdominal pain, distension, and constipation.","Abdominal X-ray showing a dilated caecum in an atypical position is suggestive of caecal volvulus.","Laparotomy is the definitive management for caecal volvulus to prevent ischaemia and perforation."],"references":["Zaberiou A, Belghali H, Souiki T, et al. Acute cecal volvulus: A diagnostic and therapeutic challenge in emergency: A case report. Ann Med Surg (Long). 2019;48:69-72. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6849140/","Abbassi I, Triki W, Trigui R, et al. Case report: Caecal volvulus management from diagnosis to treatment in a young patient. F1000Res. 2022;11:781. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9360906/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94551"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13799"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20741"},{"type":"media","id":"20742"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20741"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/qZH82ep9Q7POOR4BkMLIQH1qxkAtEd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/qZH82ep9Q7POOR4BkMLIQH1qxkAtEd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"20742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20742"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9VLEXviYkQkOhnqnQfnqXUbjRlsG20.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9VLEXviYkQkOhnqnQfnqXUbjRlsG20.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":330,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94551"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T09:11:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T09:12:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6416"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112517"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading